The best approach for your `net10.0` project is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — an established NuGet package that wraps all of `System.IO` behind injectable interfaces. No need to roll your own wrapper.

### 1. Install the packages

```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

For example, in `ReportGenerator`:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/tmp/reports", new MockDirectoryData() }
});

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Report: sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

---

**Key points:**
- `IFileSystem` gives you `.File`, `.Directory`, and `.Path` — covers all three of your statics
- `MockFileSystem` is an in-memory filesystem — fast, no disk I/O in tests
- Register as `AddSingleton` since `FileSystem` is stateless

> **Bonus:** I also see `DateTime.UtcNow`, `Environment.*`, and `Console.WriteLine` in `ReportGenerator`. On .NET 10, use the built-in **`TimeProvider`** for time, and consider small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` / `IConsole` wrappers for the others if you want full testability.
